  <section>
    <h2>How We Evaluate Pour-Over Brewers</h2>
    <p>For this roundup, we compared product positioning, brewer format, filter ecosystem, repeatability potential, and practical ownership friction. We do not claim proprietary lab validation for this page. Instead, we analyzed listings, design intent, and common user workflow patterns to answer a simple buying question: which brewer type helps most people make better coffee with fewer frustrating mornings?</p>
    <p>Our scoring heavily weighs three factors. First is <strong>repeatability</strong>—can you make a similar cup with the same recipe every day? Second is <strong>forgiveness</strong>—how badly does the cup collapse if your pour rate or grind is a little off? Third is <strong>ownership burden</strong>—how much daily cleanup, accessory dependence, and filter logistics are required to keep the brewer enjoyable after the first two weeks.</p>
    <p>That framework is why the final ranking favors brewers that work in normal kitchens, not only in ideal cafe-style prep environments. For many buyers, the "best" brewer is the one that still performs when you're short on time, using grocery-store beans, and juggling a workday. A brewer that demands perfect pouring every morning can still be excellent, but it won't be best overall for most households.</p>
  </section>

